---
import MainLayout from "../../layouts/MainLayout.astro";

const title = "Not Everything Needs to Be Manual: Small Excel Tools That Changed My Workflow";
const description =
  "A practical reflection on overlooked Excel tools in research administration, including Office Scripts, Focus Cell, and simple Excel dashboards.";
---

<MainLayout title={title} description={description}>
  <figure class="hero-image">
    <img
      src="/assets/excel-tools-header.png"
      alt="Illustrated workspace scene showing a woman at a desk with a spreadsheet on screen."
    />
  </figure>

  <section class="post-header section-shell">
    <p class="eyebrow">Featured Post</p>
    <h1>{title}</h1>
    <p class="dek">
      A few overlooked Excel tools that made repetitive reporting, spreadsheet navigation,
      and dashboard building easier to manage in research administration.
    </p>
    <p class="meta">March 24, 2026 · Featured writing</p>
  </section>

  <article class="post-body glass-card section-shell">
    <p>We all have tools we know exist but rarely use.</p>

    <p>
      In research administration, Excel is the default workspace for nearly everything—budgets,
      reports, reconciliations, quick calculations, and more. Much of that work is repetitive,
      with the structure changing little from month to month.
    </p>

    <p>Yet, I found myself rebuilding the same things repeatedly.</p>

    <p>Eventually, I realized I was spending time on tasks Excel was built to handle.</p>

    <h2>Office Scripts</h2>

    <p>
      I discovered Microsoft Office Scripts while exploring ways to automate my workflow. If you
      want to try it, you can find Office Scripts in Excel for the Web under the Automate tab.
      It’s available through most work or school Microsoft 365 accounts, and you can either record
      a script or start from examples.
    </p>

    <p>
      With so much attention on AI, it made me pause and ask a simpler question: what tools are we
      already overlooking?
    </p>

    <p>Office Scripts was one of them.</p>

    <p>
      I had been repeating the same steps—cleaning exported data, adjusting formats, and setting up
      reports the same way each time. Nothing complex, just consistent.
    </p>

    <p>
      Office Scripts lets you turn that sequence into something repeatable. For example, I automated
      a monthly process where I clean exported transaction data: removing extra columns, reformatting
      dates, and flagging missing information. Now, instead of rebuilding the process each time, I
      run the script and it handles everything in seconds.
    </p>

    <p>
      It’s not about replacing the work—it’s about standardizing the parts that don’t need manual
      attention every time.
    </p>

    <h2>“Focus Cell” Feature</h2>

    <p>
      Though simple, this feature has made a noticeable difference in how I work with larger
      spreadsheets.
    </p>

    <p>
      With long reports or dense data, it’s easy to lose your place—especially when moving quickly
      across rows and columns. I found myself double-checking my position more than I’d like to
      admit.
    </p>

    <p>
      A focus-style setup—where the active row and column are highlighted—eliminates that problem
      almost immediately. In Excel, go to View → Show → Focus Cell. It keeps your place anchored by
      clearly showing both the row and column of the cell you’re working in.
    </p>

    <p>
      It doesn’t calculate or automate—it simply provides a clear visual anchor while you work.
    </p>

    <p>That small shift has mattered more than I expected.</p>

    <h2>Simple Dashboards</h2>

    <p>This is another one that sounds more complicated than it actually is.</p>

    <p>
      By dashboard, I don’t mean anything overly designed or presentation-ready. I simply mean a
      single place for key information—something you can glance at and immediately understand what’s
      going on.
    </p>

    <p>
      For me, that usually includes current balances, monthly burn, and anything trending over or
      under expectation.
    </p>

    <p>
      Before this, I was jumping between multiple tabs trying to piece together the full picture.
      The information was there—it just wasn’t centralized.
    </p>

    <p>
      Pulling those pieces into a simple dashboard reduced the back-and-forth and made it easier to
      catch issues early.
    </p>

    <p>It’s less about building something impressive and more about building something useful.</p>

    <h2>Excel Dashboards</h2>

    <p>
      Most of the time, the data already exists—it’s just spread across tabs or buried in a larger
      dataset.
    </p>

    <p>
      Once your data is structured—even something as simple as organizing it into a clean table—you
      can start building. PivotTables make it easy to summarize what matters, whether that is time,
      category, or account, and charts turn those summaries into something easier to read.
    </p>

    <div class="start-box">
      <p class="start-label">If you want to get started:</p>
      <ol>
        <li>Make sure your data is clean and organized into a table with headers.</li>
        <li>Insert a PivotTable on a new sheet and use it to summarize the numbers you care about most.</li>
        <li>Add a chart based on that summary.</li>
        <li>Move those pieces onto a single sheet to create a dashboard view.</li>
        <li>Add slicers if you want an easy way to filter the information and adjust the view without rebuilding everything.</li>
      </ol>
    </div>

    <p>
      Even with just a few steps, you end up with a live snapshot that updates as your data changes.
    </p>

    <p>
      What really changed things for me was the interactivity. Instead of jumping between tabs,
      everything lives in one place and updates together.
    </p>

    <p>
      If you want to take it further, learning Power BI—or working with your IT team to build
      something more structured—is a great next step. But even within Excel, a simple dashboard goes
      a long way.
    </p>

    <div class="closing-note">
      <p>
        We spend a lot of time looking for new tools, but sometimes the better move is just using
        the ones we already have more intentionally. An easy way to make the most of these small
        improvements is by sharing what you've built with colleagues. For example, you can save time
        across your team by sharing useful Excel templates or scripts, or storing them in a shared
        folder everyone can access. Even a quick demonstration during a meeting can spark ideas and
        help others standardize their workflow. This kind of sharing makes it easier for research
        administrators to lift up their whole group, not just their individual processes.
      </p>
    </div>
  </article>

  <style>
    .hero-image {
      margin: 0 0 1.5rem;
      border-radius: var(--radius-xl);
      overflow: hidden;
      box-shadow: var(--shadow);
      background: #eaf0f5;
    }

    .hero-image img {
      display: block;
      width: 100%;
      height: auto;
      aspect-ratio: 16 / 8.5;
      object-fit: cover;
    }

    .post-header {
      margin-bottom: 1.5rem;
    }

    .eyebrow {
      display: inline-block;
      margin: 0 0 1rem;
      padding: 0.45rem 0.8rem;
      border-radius: 999px;
      background: var(--accent-soft);
      color: var(--accent);
      font-size: 0.88rem;
      font-weight: 700;
      letter-spacing: 0.03em;
    }

    h1 {
      margin: 0 0 0.9rem;
      font-size: clamp(2.3rem, 5vw, 3.7rem);
      line-height: 1.05;
      letter-spacing: -0.035em;
      color: #163127;
      font-weight: 700;
    }

    .dek {
      margin: 0 0 0.9rem;
      font-size: 1.08rem;
      line-height: 1.85;
      color: var(--muted);
      max-width: 44rem;
    }

    .meta {
      margin: 0;
      font-size: 0.95rem;
      color: #6b7280;
    }

    .post-body {
      padding: clamp(1.35rem, 2.5vw, 2.2rem);
    }

    .post-body p {
      margin: 0 0 1.2rem;
      font-size: 1.08rem;
      line-height: 1.95;
      color: var(--text);
    }

    .post-body h2 {
      margin: 2.2rem 0 0.85rem;
      font-size: 1.5rem;
      line-height: 1.22;
      color: #18382d;
      font-weight: 700;
    }

    .post-body ol {
      margin: 0.45rem 0 0 1.35rem;
      padding: 0;
    }

    .post-body li {
      margin: 0 0 0.55rem;
      font-size: 1.05rem;
      line-height: 1.85;
      color: var(--text);
    }

    .start-box {
      margin: 1.5rem 0;
      padding: 1.05rem 1.15rem;
      border-radius: 18px;
      background: #f8fbff;
      border: 1px solid rgba(58, 88, 120, 0.12);
    }

    .start-label {
      margin: 0 0 0.6rem;
      font-weight: 700;
      color: #234;
      font-size: 1rem;
    }

    .closing-note {
      margin-top: 1.6rem;
      padding: 1rem 1.05rem;
      border-left: 4px solid var(--accent);
      background: rgba(38, 78, 65, 0.06);
      border-radius: 14px;
    }

    .closing-note p {
      margin: 0;
    }

    @media (max-width: 720px) {
      h1 {
        font-size: clamp(2rem, 9vw, 2.7rem);
      }

      .dek,
      .post-body p,
      .post-body li {
        font-size: 1rem;
        line-height: 1.85;
      }

      .post-body h2 {
        font-size: 1.35rem;
      }
    }
  </style>
</MainLayout>